At the moment that human societ-y commenced, man was already in possession of language, which, therefore, could not possibly have originated in a tacit compact: though it be admitted, that a compact of this, οι· of a similar nature, has much to do, in regulating the copious dialects of cultivated life, From these dialects, the original speech of man’s first parents must have differed widely, in its com· pass, and structure.

Language being only a medium for the expression, and communication of human ideas, and sensations, can be no further necessary, than as it is conduc-ive to these ends. And as all human societies, however simple, and rude, possess language enough to communicate their usual range of ideas,—but no more,—we may, of course, presume that such was the case with Adam.

The compass of his language could only have been com· mensurate with his occasions for speech.
